The Governors of the six South-West states are expected to meet with police chiefs on Wednesday ahead of Thursday’s inauguration of ‘Amotekun’, the region’s security outfit. Our correspondent gathered that the meeting is scheduled for Ibadan where the security outfit will be unveiled. Operation ‘Amotekun’ was carefully designed to curb armed banditry, kidnapping for ransom and other forms of criminality. It was also gathered, that all the equipment, including operational vehicles, motorcycles and communication gadgets would have been moved from the states to Ibadan before the meeting that will be presided over by Ondo State governor, Oluwarotimi Akedolu, who is chairman of South West Governors’ Forum. Expected at the meeting are Governors Seyi Makinde (Oyo); Kayode Fayemi (Ekiti); Adegboyega Oyetola (Osun); Dapo Abiodun (Ogun) and Babjide Sanwo-Olu (Lagos). The meeting is to allow the governors and the police chiefs to finalise how the outfit will operate for proper understanding before the launch. It was learnt that the governors had been in constant communication in the last 10 days to firm up the role which conventional and unconventional security personnel will play in Amotekun. Commissioners of police in the region will meet under the coordination of the Assistant-Inspectors General (AIGs) in the region before the meeting with the governors.        